						               													<description>ZAG is a visual game about solving graphic puzzles in zig-zag.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each player has a mini-board, five double-sided tiles and a deck of cards showing visual challenging patterns to solve as fast as one can.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each card shows a number of tiles to be placed and solve its pattern, from only two to five tiles. But don&amp;acute;t be fooled. Sometimes, a two piece puzzle may be surprisingly challenging.&amp;#10; The deck comes with tutorial cards that help players learn the tile placing rules and practice a little bit before diving into the real ZAG. First: be careful, the board has a specific orientation. Second: tiles are always placed on the board inside its limits. Third: tiles are always placed parallel to the board&amp;acute;s sides, so they are never placed diagonally. And fourth, tiles never overlap!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game comes with two decks of puzzles: a beginner&amp;acute;s set of 12 cards with hints that show a thumbnail of each tile used to solve that puzzle. Once those cards become too easy, and one might look for a more challenging experience, there is a set of 45 cards showing only the puzzle, without any hint whatsoever.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;A game of ZAG is played in rounds. &amp;#10;Each round, give each player a card and they have to solve it simultaneously.&amp;#10;When someone has finished, flip the card face down and say: - ZAG!&amp;#10;Wait until everyone finishes, check if the puzzles were correctly solved and earn the card as points.&amp;#10;After a round for each count of tiles, from 2 to 5, the game is over.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
